            It can be proven (using calculus) that at any given point the slope of a function of the form
            <m>y=b^x</m> is directly proportional to the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the point; the 
            proportionality constant is whatever the slope is at the point <m>(0,1)</m>.
            That is, for functions of the form <m>y=b^x</m>, at any given point <m>(x,y)</m>  
            the slope of the function is <m>ky</m> where <m>k</m> is the slope of the curve at <m>(0,1)</m>.
            For example, the function of the form <m>y=b^x</m> that has a slope of <m>4</m> at the point
            <m>(0,1)</m> has a slope of <m>12</m> at the point where the <m>y</m>-coordinate is <m>3</m> and a slope of <m>80</m> 
            at the point where <m>y</m>-coordinate is <m>20</m>.

            One implication of the proportionality between the slope of the function 
            and the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the function is that the function of the 
            form <m>y=b^x</m> that has a slope of one at <m>(0,1)</m> has a very unique 
            property -- at any given point the slope of the function is exactly 
            equal to the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the point. As suggested in <xref ref="exp-fig-eusingslopese"/>, 
            it turns out that the base that creates this unique situation is that 
            same number that showed up in the continuously compounded interest 
            application, the number <m>e</m>. So on the graph of <m>y=e^x</m>, at any given 
            point the slope of the curve is exactly equal to the <m>y</m>-coordinate of 
            the point.

