<title>Newton's Law of Cooling</title>
<statement>
            You may have noticed that when you leave a cup of hot coffee in a room, 
            the coffee's temperature will decrease to room temperature. Provided that 
            the difference between the temperature of the liquid and its surrounding 
            is not too great, then <em>Newton's Law of Cooling</em> applies.

            One day you buy a cup of coffee that starts at <quantity><mag>90</mag><unit base="degreeCelsius"/></quantity>, 
            and you are stood outside where the temperature is <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="degreeCelsius"/></quantity>. Let
            <m>T(t)</m> represent the temperature of your coffee at time <m>t</m> (in minutes) since you bought it.
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                What is <m>T(0)</m>?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>T(0)=90</m>. 
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Do you expect <m>T(t)</m> to tend toward a value as <m>t\rightarrow\infty</m>?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>T(t)\rightarrow 0</m> as <m>t\rightarrow\infty</m>. 
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                The temperature of the coffee <em>decreases</em> at a continuous rate of <quantity><mag>7</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> per minute. Write a
                formula for <m>T(t)</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>T(t)=90e^{-0.07t}</m> 
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                According to your model, what is the temperature of the coffee <quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="minute"/></quantity> after you bought it?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>T(10)=90e^{-0.07\cdot 10}\approx 45</m>; the temperature of the coffee
                  is approximately <quantity><mag>45</mag><unit base="degreeCelsius"/></quantity>.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                According to your model, how long after you bought your coffee is 
                the temperature of the coffee <quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="degreeCelsius"/></quantity>?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We need to solve the equation <m>5=90e^{-0.07t}</m> for <m>t</m>. Using a graphing calculator, 
                  we find <m>t\approx 41.29</m>. The coffee will be <quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="degreeCelsius"/></quantity> approximately <quantity><mag>41</mag><unit base="minute"/></quantity> 
                  after it was bought.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                According to your model, is the temperature of the coffee ever <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="degreeCelsius"/></quantity>? 
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  No -- the model is limited in this way. 
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            </exercisegroup>

