<title>The RC circuit</title>
<statement>
            A <em>capacitor</em> is a device that stores electrical energy in the form of charged particles.
            The <em>voltage</em> on the capacitor is a result of the electric field created by the particles and
            is proportional to the amount of charge stored. A <em>resistor</em> is a device that dissipates
            electrical energy. If a capacitor is charged up and then connected across a resistor, the
            capacitor discharges and the voltage drops.

            The voltage (in \si{\volt}), on the capacitor as it is being discharged is modeled by the
            function <m>V</m> that has formula 
            <me>
            V(t)=V_0e^{-\frac{t}{RC}}
            </me>
            where <m>V_0</m> is the initial capacitor voltage, <m>R</m> is the value of the
            resistor (in \si{\ohm}), <m>C</m> is the value of the capacitor (in \si{\farad}) and <m>t</m> is time (in \si{\second}).
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Suppose that a <m>2\times 10^{-6}</m>-farad capacitor, initially charged up 
                to <quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="volt"/></quantity>, is connected across a 50,000-ohm resistor. 
                Write the formula for <m>V(t)</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>V(t)=10e^{-\frac{t}{0.1}}=10e^{-10t}</m>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exp-prob-circuittab">
              <statement>
                Construct a table of values of <m>V(t)</m> using <m>t=0,0.1,...,0.5</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <table>
<tabular>[t]{S[table-format=1.1]S[table-format=2.3]} 
                  <thead>
                  <cell><m>t</m></cell>            &amp; <cell><m>V(t)</m></cell>       \\
                  <cell>(\si{\second</cell>)} &amp; <cell>(\si{\volt</cell>)} \\
                  </thead>
<cell>0.0</cell>&amp;<cell>10.000</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.1</cell>&amp;<cell>3.369</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.2</cell>&amp;<cell>1.353</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.3</cell>&amp;<cell>0.498</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.4</cell>&amp;<cell>0.183</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.5</cell>&amp;<cell>0.067</cell>\\  \lastline
                  </tabular>
</table>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Based on your answer to <xref ref="exp-prob-circuittab"/>, do you think the 
                graph of <m>y=V(t)</m> will be concave up or concave down? Why?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Concave up, since the slopes between successive entries 
                  are increasing by becoming less negative.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Graph the function <m>V</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>y=V(t)</m> is shown below.

                  <image>
                    <latex-image-code>
                      <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[
                      framed,
                      xmin=-0.2,xmax=1,
                      ymin=-1,ymax=11,
                      xtick={0.2,0.4,...,0.8},
                      minor xtick={0.1,0.3,...,0.9},
                      ytick={2,4,...,10},
                      minor ytick={1,3,...,9},
                      xlabel={<m>t</m>},
                      grid=both,
                      ]
                      \addplot+[-&gt;]expression[domain=0:1,samples=50]{10*exp(-10*x)};
                      \end{axis}
                      \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                  </image>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                By what percentage has the voltage decreased on the capacitor after <quantity><mag>0.1</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>? 
                After <quantity><mag>0.2</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  After <quantity><mag>0.1</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>, the voltage on the capacitor has decreased by about
                  <quantity><mag>63</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity>. After <quantity><mag>0.2</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>, the voltage on the 
                  capacitor has decreased by about <quantity><mag>86</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity>.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            </exercisegroup>

