                Suppose that a 10-volt battery is connected to a <m>2\times 10^{-6}</m>-farad capacitor 
                and a 50,000-ohm resistor.  Write the formula for <m>V(t)</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>V(t)=10( 1-e^{-0.1t} )</m> 
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exp-prob-chargecaptab">
              <statement>
                Construct a table of values of <m>V(t)</m> using <m>t=0,0.1,...,0.5</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <table>
<tabular>[t]{S[table-format=1.1]S[table-format=1.3]} 
                  <thead>
                  <cell><m>t</m></cell>            &amp; <cell><m>V(t)</m></cell>       \\
                  <cell>(\si{\second</cell>)} &amp; <cell>(\si{\volt</cell>)} \\
                  </thead>
<cell>0.0</cell>&amp;<cell>0.000</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.1</cell>&amp;<cell>6.321</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.2</cell>&amp;<cell>8.647</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.3</cell>&amp;<cell>9.502</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.4</cell>&amp;<cell>9.817</cell>\\  \normalline
<cell>0.5</cell>&amp;<cell>9.933</cell>\\  \lastline
                  </tabular>
</table>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Based on your answer to <xref ref="exp-prob-chargecaptab"/>, do you think the 
                graph of <m>y=V(t)</m> will be concave up or concave down? Why?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  The graph will be concave down since the slopes between successive
                  entries are decreasing by becoming less positive.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Graph the function <m>V</m>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  <m>y=V(t)</m> is shown below.

                  <image>
                    <latex-image-code>
                      <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[
                      framed,
                      xmin=-0.2,xmax=1,
                      ymin=-1,ymax=11,
                      xtick={0.2,0.4,...,0.8},
                      minor xtick={0.1,0.3,...,0.9},
                      ytick={2,4,...,10},
                      minor ytick={1,3,...,9},
                      xlabel={<m>t</m>},
                      grid=both,
                      ]
                      \addplot+[-&gt;]expression[domain=0:1,samples=50]{10*(1-exp(-10*x))};
                      \end{axis}
                      \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                  </image>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                After <quantity><mag>0.1</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>, the voltage on the capicitor is 
                what percentage of the battery voltage? After <quantity><mag>0.2</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>?
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  After <quantity><mag>0.1</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>, the capacitor has charged up to about
                  <quantity><mag>63</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> of the battery voltage. After <quantity><mag>0.2</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity>,
                  the capacitor has charged up to about <quantity><mag>86</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> of the 
                  battery voltage.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                Notice that even though the charge on the capacitor increasing, the formula modeling
                the voltage contains a decaying exponential. Explain why, mathematically, the function <m>V</m> is
                increasing even though it contains a decaying exponential.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  The value of the function can increase even though the exponential term is decaying
                  because it is being subtracted from <m>1</m>. As the exponential term decreases, the difference
                  between its value and <m>1</m> increases, creating an increasing function.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </exercise>
