                Using two ordered pairs, <m>(0,4800)</m> and <m>(15,194154)</m>, and assuming that an exponential model is appropriate, we can 
                show that a formula that approximates <m>W</m> is
                <md>
                W(t) &amp; =      4800\left( \frac{194154}{4800} \right)^{\sfrac{t}{15}}                  \\
                &amp; =      4800\left( \left( \frac{194154}{4800} \right)^{\sfrac{1}{15}} \right)^t \\
                &amp; \approx 4800(1.279756)^t                                                          
                </md>
                Using a table of values or a graph, find when the world's wind power capacity will be <quantity><mag>250000</mag><unit base="watt" prefix="mega"/></quantity>.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Using a table of values, we find that <m>W(16)\approx 248470</m>, and <m>W(17)\approx 317980</m>. We conclude that, 
                  according to the model, the world's wind power capacity will be <quantity><mag>250000</mag><unit base="watt" prefix="mega"/></quantity> in early 2012. 
                </p>
              </solution>
