<title>Linear, exponential, or neither?</title>
<statement>
            Decide if the function that is described is more like an exponential function, a linear function, or neither.
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                The number of plants that germinate is a function of the number of seeds sown.
                For a particular crop of peas, exactly <quantity><mag>70</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> of the seeds sown germinate. 
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Linear. 
                </p>
              </solution>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Linear. The function can be modeled by <m>g(x)=0.7x</m>, where <m>g(x)</m> is the number 
                  of plants that germinate and <m>x</m> is the number of seeds sown. An increase in the <m>x</m> 
                  value results in an increase in the <m>g(x)</m> value by <quantity><mag>70</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> of the <m>x</m> value. 
                </p>
              </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                The number of tulip bulbs in a garden is a function of the number of years since first planting.
                Every year, each of the tulip bulbs divides into two. 
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Exponential. 
                </p>
              </solution>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Exponential. The function can be modeled by <m>f(x)=2^x</m>, where <m>f(x)</m> is the 
                  number of bulbs <m>x</m> years since first planting. Every increase in the <m>x</m> value 
                  results in the doubling of the value of <m>f(x)</m>.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                The amount of money in Ross' bank account is a function of the number of years since the account was opened. 	
                Every year the amount of money in Ross' account increases by <dollar/>5000. 
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Linear. 
                </p>
              </solution>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Linear. The function can be modeled by <m>g(x)=5000x</m>, where <m>g(x)</m> is the amount of money 
                  in the bank account and <m>x</m> is the number of years since I opened the account. Every 
                  increase in the <m>x</m> value results in an increase in the value <m>g(x)</m> by 5000.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                The amount of money in Serena's account is a function of the number 
                of years since she opened the account.
                Every year the amount of money Serena's account increases by <quantity><mag>2</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> of the amount that was in the 
                account the year before. 
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Exponential.
                </p>
              </solution>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Exponential. The function can be modeled by <m>f(x)=1.02^x</m>, where <m>f(x)</m> is the amount of money 
                  in the bank account and <m>x</m> is the number of years since I opened the account. Every increase 
                  in the <m>x</m> value results in <quantity><mag>102</mag><unit base="percent"/></quantity> of the value of <m>f(x)</m>.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              <statement>
                The number of pages you still have to read in a book is a function of the page number you're on.
              </statement>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Linear.
                </p>
              </solution>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  The function can be modeled by <m>g(x)=b-x</m> where <m>b</m> is the total number of pages in the book, 
                  <m>x</m> is the page number that you're on and <m>g(x)</m> is the number of pages left to read. For every 
                  one page you read, you have one page fewer still to read.
                </p>
              </answer>
            </exercise>
            </exercisegroup>

